                </div>
                <div class="col-xl-12">
                    <h2 class="text-center">Main Cause Of A Website Low Speed</h2>
                    <p>Run a speed test just to be well aware of what you are dealing with. If you are not satisfied with the result, we are right here to guide you. There are lots of effective ways to make your website work better. An effective list of ways is given below and you are welcomed to take a look.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-xl-6 col-lg-6 col-md-6">
                    <h2 class="text-center">CDN (Content Delivery Network)</h2>
                    <p>CDN means Content Delivery Network. It is very useful for speed optimization. CDN supplies the content from his nearby station to the users. So, it takes a short time to load, which will help speed optimization.You may use a single server to host your website. In that case, all the user requests are sent to the same hardware. Due to this, the time required to optimize each request extends. Also, if the user’s location is far away from the server, the load time will extend in that case.CDN makes it easier for users by sending user requests to the nearest station. In that case, the website works quicker, the page load time gets lessened, and users get a faster content delivery. The whole CDN process can be expensive but effective indeed.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-xl-6 col-lg-6 col-md-6">
                    <h2 class="text-center">Hosting</h2>
                    <p>Hosting is an important part of speed optimization. We usually use shared hosting, and it is very popular. Before taking hosting, we have to select the best hosting that helps much for speed. We can see the variation in hosting- 1.Shared Hosting 2.Virtual Private Servers Hosting 3.Dedicated Server Shared hosting. It is a less costly way to establish your website online. A fast web host works the best on such terms. So that your website gets a better optimization. You share CPU, RAM, disk space with other websites in shared hosting. But it will be slower than a dedicated server. Virtual private servers are your perfect choice if you are looking for a moderate service in a moderate investment. Though you will be sharing the server with other users, you will have a part to call your own. Other users will not be influenced by your configuration. A dedicated server comes with the most costly hosting. But it will be your own physical server.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-xl-6 col-lg-6 col-md-6">
                    <h2 class="text-center">Size of Images</h2>
                    <p>Attractive and quality images play a vital role in impressing the visitors. I mean who does not love eye-catching images? Qualities photos, graphics, images can bring more visitors to your e-commerce site. It improves the engagement of the audience. But also, the main barrier to speed is big-size images on the website. Finally, images reduce the page speed every time. So, before using images, we have to reduce the size of the images. If you do not want to compromise with the picture quality, you can use tools like Imagine Optime, JPEGmini, Kraken, etc. The whole process may seem lengthy, but it is effective. There is always another way. You can use HTML-responsive images and tools to lessen the size of images.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-xl-6 col-lg-6 col-md-6">
                    <h2 class="text-center">Excessive Plugins Use</h2>
                    <p>Plugins are indeed essential to run a website. They add certain features to your site. But using a lot of plugins might bring you trouble. It requires a lot of supplements and makes the website slow. It also welcomes security issues. So what do you do in that case? We suggest you run a test and identify unnecessary plugins. Keep the plugins that are helping to increase the attractiveness of your website and delete the unnecessary ones. A good number of plugins might do good for your site, but the quality is also a factor. Unnecessary plugins are not helpful for any website. More plugins hamper the speed of the website. So, if you delete unnecessary plugins, then speed will automatically increase.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-xl-6 col-lg-6 col-md-6">
                    <h2 class="text-center">Database</h2>
                    <p>Using a CMS that comes with tricky plugins will extend the size of your database, causing your website to work slower. As an example, we present the WordPress CMS store which gathers blog posts, comments, and various data that require a lot of storage. Database optimization is another important way to improve your speed. In all CMS, if you use plugins, your database will take space, and loading speed will increase. So, you have to optimize your database as it is a very effective way</p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-xl-6 col-lg-6 col-md-6">
                    <h2 class="text-center">404 Error</h2>
                    <p>404 error is another issue to high web speed optimization. 404 error means the page you search is not gotten. It takes time to search and get the message. To solve this, we can use a redirected plugin. To rectify 404 errors, we suggest you use detection tools and plugins. Run the resource using exterior tools for error identification. Got your 404 errors detected? Now you need to examine the traffic they cause. Keep the dead links aside which no longer bring visitors. But if you notice otherwise, fix it by setting redirects for exterior links and figuring out the link addresses used for interior ones.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-xl-6 col-lg-6 col-md-6">
                    <h2 class="text-center">Web Fonts</h2>
                    <p>Web fonts make your site alluring enough to bring visitors. But everything comes with a negative size. It has a bad impact on your website speed. It brings more HTTP requests causing page rendering. We have listed 3 ways to help you in this case.</p>
                    <ul class="web-list">
                        <li>For advanced browsers use advanced formats WOFF2</li>
                        <li>Stick to choose the required styles</li>
                        <li>Add the character sets which would be used on the website.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="col-xl-6 col-lg-6 col-md-6">
                    <h2 class="text-center">Redirects</h2>
                    <p>Redirection is a great problem for speed optimization. It makes extra HTTP requests that create a bad impression. So, keep the redirects lowkey or abandon them permanently.</p>
                    <p>Do a scanning and recognize the redirects on your webpage. Consider using Screaming Frog for fast identification. If some redirects are serving you for good, keep them and eliminate the crucial ones.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-xl-6 col-lg-6 col-md-6">
                    <h2 class="text-center">Website Caching</h2>
                    <p>Caching is when your website saves the current state of data until the next update. If a good number of users are spending time on your website simultaneously, it takes more time to deliver the webpage to the individual users which is super time-consuming. But if cached, the webpage does not have to render on repeat. For a VPS/dedicated server, you can station caching right beneath the general setting. If you are a WordPress user, you can use plugins like- W3 Super Cache/W3 Total Cache.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-xl-6 col-lg-6 col-md-6">
                    <h2 class="text-center">Site Not Optimized For Mobile</h2>
                    <p>A good number of users use mobile for browsing. So, you have to give equal attention to your site’s device compatibility. Because it has a huge influence on your site’s ranking, make sure your site is user-friendly to Android/IOS users. As there are many competitors of your in the e-commerce world, your webpage requires to be fast. Run a test to know your site’s average speed time on 3G. For that, you can get help from the Best WP Developer.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-xl-6 col-lg-6 col-md-6">
                    <h2 class="text-center">GZIP Compression Issue</h2>
                    <p>If you use the Gzip compression method, the file size will get decreased. It shortens server reply time and reduces HTTP requests. The file works like a zipper as it gets compressed. When the file is presented to the visitors, they can unzip it and see the inner contents. You can use this technique for all your website files. You can activate Gzip by attaching lines of the code or an attribute known as gzip.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-xl-6 col-lg-6 col-md-6">
                    <h2 class="text-center">Leverage Browser Caching</h2>
                    <p>To make it easier, we have to be concerned about caching. Browsers cache a good amount of data- images, stylesheets, JavaScript files, and so on. When a user revisits your site, the data remains reloaded due to browser caching. YSlow tool keeps you updated about the expiration date of the cache. You can manually set the expiration date by setting your expiration header. You can set the time to a year as it sounds reasonable.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-xl-12">
                    <h2 class="text-center">JavaScript & CSS Minification</h2>
                    <p>In case you own a website that has a large number of JavaScript and CSS files, you will likely get a lot of HTTP requests. It causes trouble when internet users need to access certain files. These requests are taken care of one by one and the whole process slows down your website. JavaScript and CSS code takes time to load on the website. As a result, your website will take time to show the result. Then the loading speed will increase. To solve this issue, you have to compress the JavaScript and CSS file. Indeed it will work and lessen your website slowdown issue.</p>
                </div>
